  {
    "type": "EXEGETICAL (ORIGINAL LANGUAGES)",
    "name": "Pulpit Commentary",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_sub_title",
        "text": "Verse 32.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " - ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_word",
        "text": "An hole in the top of it",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". A mere circular hole for the head to go through, unaccompanied by a slit or longitudinal opening. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_word",
        "text": "In the midst of it",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". Midway between the two arm-holes. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_word",
        "text": "A binding of woven work round about the hole of it",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". This would strengthen the edge of the opening) and prevent it from tearing or fraying. The binding was probably sewn on after the frock was woven. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_word",
        "text": "As it were the hole of an habergeon",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". Linen corselets or habergeons have been found in Egypt. They were sometimes covered with metal scales, and were of the make here indicated. (See the author's ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "History",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " of Eg",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "y",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "pt, vol. 1. p. 446.) The word here used for \"habergeon\" (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "takharah",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ") is Egyptian. Exodus 28:32",
        "children": []
      },
